 say that i was born and raised in trail british columbia a town of about eight zero zero zero with lots of ice in the winter my father did radio play by play for the local team the trail smokeaters who by the way were the last canadian team to win the world championship back in one nine six one i was on skates almost as soon as i could walk and have been playing recreational hockey for about three five years when was the last time you saw a hockey league in the inner city the insurance alone is a big enough barrier the inner city isn t the only place that is poor i think the biggest barrier to hockey in the inner city is no ice to play on lack of ice is a big factor but costs is a bigger factor both my kids play for the santa clara valley hockey association and this season which just ended cost me seven five per kid for membership in hockey usa plus seven five zero per kid for club dues the hockey usa fees cover excess medical insurance and the club dues cover ice time officials trophies etc other areas have similar fees unless the city government subsidises some of the costs as stockton does by the way most ice arenas are located in what could be called the inner city areas eastridge and vallco are exceptions redwood city s rink is in an industrial area on bay rd near one zero one berkeley s is near ashby and martin luther king stockton s is in oak park sacramento s is in an older section of downtown i forget the name of the street fresno s is out on the edge of town just west of nine nine santa rosa s is a nice rink but it s in an older section of town dublin s is outside of town off five eight zero most of the rinks are old and expensive to run with huge electric bills and insurance premiums if you want to buy ice time expect to pay around one zero zero per hour at any of these rinks some of them give you a six zero minute hour for your money others give you a five zero minute hour and include the resurfacing time in the fee alan hepburn a man doesn t know what 